31:119.name: Style=Standard, State=Enabled
31:119.description:
Standard Icon buttons are low-emphasis buttons.
They are used for the lowest priority actions, especially when presenting multiple options.

Icon buttons can be placed on a variety of backgrounds. Until the button is interacted with, its container isn’t visible.

31:453.name: Configuration=Small, Elevation=flat
31:453.description: The top app bar provides content and actions related to the current screen. It’s used for branding, screen titles, navigation, and actions.

31:692.name: Style=Filled, State=Enabled, Show Icon=False
31:692.description:
Filled buttons are high-emphasis buttons.
They have the most visual impact after the FAB, and should be used for important, final actions that complete a flow, like "Save", "Join now", or "Confirm".

31:2.name: Navigation Rail
31:2.description:
The rail is a side navigation component that displays three to seven app destinations and, optionally, a floating action button (FAB). Each destination is represented by an icon and label text.

The rail can serve as the sole navigation component on larger screen sizes, such as desktops and tablets.

🛠 Additional options
Segments - Can be edited by selecting individual segments and  selecting states, labels, and badges from the variant properties.

31:42.name: Icon button
31:42.description:
Icon buttons display actions in a compact layout. Icon buttons can represent opening actions such as opening an overflow menu or search, or represent binary actions that can be toggled on and off, such as favorite or bookmark.

Icon buttons can be grouped together or they can stand alone.

31:127.name: FAB
31:127.description: Floating action buttons (FABs) help people take primary actions on a screen. The FAB appears in front of all other content on screen, and is recognizable for its rounded shape and icon in the center.

31:448.name: Top app bar
31:448.description: Use a top app bar to provide content and actions related to a current screen, such as navigation, screen headlines, and actions.

31:519.name: Button
31:519.description: Buttons communicate actions that users can take. They are typically placed throughout your UI, in places like Dialogs, Modal windows, Forms, Cards and Toolbars

31:701.name: linear-determinate
31:701.description: Determinate indicators display how long a process will take. They should be used when the process completion rate can be detected.
